<section><title>Geogebra Activities</title>

<worksheet><title>Geogebra Worksheet 1: Constructing Symmetric Points</title>
      <p>
        At <url href="https://www.geogebra.org">geogebra.org</url> look for the list of apps under the heading <em>Powerful Math Apps</em>.  For this we want to use the app <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/geometry">geometry</url>.
      </p>
      <p>
        When you open the Geometry app, you should see a blank canvas on the right and a pallette of tools on the left.  We will want more than the basic tools, so click on <em>MORE</em> to see them all.  
      </p>
      <p>
        To familiarize yourself with this app, work through the following constructions.
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Construct a circle.  Label the center of the circle <m>Z_0</m>. Label the circle itself as <m>c</m>.  One quirk with Geogebra is that points must be labelled by capital letters, and lines and circles must be labelled by lower case letters.
          </p>
          <p>
            To change an object's label, click the <em>Move</em> tool and select the object.  A window should appear with a text box.  Click that to change the label.  To get <m>Z_0</m> type <em>Z_0</em>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise><title>Construct <m>z^*</m> if <m>z</m> is inside the circle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this exercise we construct the point symmetric to <m>Z</m> with respect to the circle <m>c</m> where <m>Z</m> is inside the circle.
            <ol label="a.">
              <li>
                Construct a point inside the circle, and label it <m>Z</m>.  Then construct the ray <m>\vec{Z_0Z}</m>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Construct the line perpendicular to ray <m>\vec{Z_0Z}</m> at the point <m>Z</m>.  Call this line <m>m</m> (lines get lower case letters).
              </li>
              <li>
                With the point tool selected, define one of the points at which <m>m</m> intersects the circle and label this point <m>T</m>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Construct segment <m>Z_0T</m> and then construct the line perpendicular to this segment at <m>T</m>.  Call this line <m>n</m>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Define the point at which line <m>n</m> intersects ray <m>\overrightarrow{Z_0Z}</m>.  This is the point symmetric to <m>Z</m> with respect to circle <m>c</m>.  Label this point <m>Z_s</m>.
              </li>
            </ol>
            </p> 
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>Hide intermediate constructions</title>  
        <statement>
          <p>
            Select the Show/Hide Object tool and click on these intermediate constructions: ray <m>\vec{Z_0Z}</m>, lines <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, the point <m>T</m>, and segment <m>Z_0T</m>.  Now click on the Move tool (or another tool).  Those objects (and hopefully nothing else) will disappear.  To get them to reappear, click on the Show/Hide Object tool again.  The objects marked for hiding will appear faiter than the other objects.  Note:  If you simply delete these objects all other objects depending on them (like <m>Z_s</m>) will vanish too and we donâ€™t want that!!
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <p>
        Congratulations!!  You constructed the point symmetric to <m>Z</m> with respect to <m>c</m>.  Now click on the Move tool and drag the point <m>Z</m> around inside the circle.  Admire how <m>Z^*</m> follows dutifully around and is always the point symmetric to <m>Z</m>.  Notice how <m>Z</m> and <m>Z_s</m> get closer together as you near the circle, and how <m>Z_s</m> rushes excitedly toward infinity, like a dog wanting to please its master, as <m>Z</m> marches toward <m>Z_0</m>.  What happens if <m>Z</m> moves outside the circle?  Can you construct <m>Z_s</m> if <m>Z</m> is outside <m>c</m>?
      </p>

      <exercise><title>Construct <m>z^*</m> if <m>z</m> is outside the circle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Move <m>Z</m> outside the circle and complete these steps.
          <ol label="a.">
              <li> 
                Construct the circle having diameter <m>Z_0Z</m>.  Plot a point  at which this circle intersects <m>c</m> and label this point  <m>T</m>.
                <hint> Begin by finding the midpoint of segment <m>Z_0Z</m>.</hint>
              </li>
              <li>
                Construct the perpendicular to <m>Z_0Z</m> through <m>T</m>. 
              </li>
              <li>
                Let <m>Z_s</m> be the intersection of this perpendicular with segment <m>Z_0Z</m>.
              </li>
              <li> 
                Hide intermediate constructions so that only <m>Z</m> and <m>Z_s</m> remain.  If you move <m>Z</m> back inside the circle, the <q>other</q> <m>Z_s</m> should still reappear.  Check to make sure.
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>The symmetry point tool</title>
      	<statement>
      		<p>
      			Now that you know how to construct symmetric points whether <m>Z</m> is inside or outside a circle, I would like to point out that Geogebra has a ready-made tool for finding symmetry points, the reflect across a circle tool.  We will use this tool to speed up future constructions that involve symmetry points, especially constructions in the hyperbolic plane of Chapter 5.
      		</p>
      	</statement>
      </exercise>
    </worksheet>

<worksheet><title>Geogebra Worksheet 2: Constructing Type I and Type II clines of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m></title>
       <p>
        At <url href="https://www.geogebra.org">geogebra.org</url> open the app <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/geometry">geometry</url>.
      </p>
      <exercise><title>The Type I cline of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> through <m>z</m></title>
        <statement>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Plot three points labelled <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>Z</m> on your canvas.
            </li>
            <li>
              With the perpendicular bisector tool construct the perpendicular bisector between <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, and the perpendicular bisector between <m>P</m> and <m>Z</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the point at which these perpendicular bisectors intersect, label this point <m>O</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the circle centered at <m>O</m> through <m>Z</m>.  This is the type I cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Hide intermediate constructions so that all we see on the canvas are the three points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>Z</m>, and the type I cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>.  Drag <m>Z</m> around to check the dynamic nature of your construction.  
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Two comments: First, this construction assumes <m>Z</m> is not on the line through <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.  (If <m>Z</m> is on this line, then the type I cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m> is this line.)  Second, <em>Geogebra</em> has a tool for constructing this cline, the tool <q>circle through 3 points</q>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="wk-typeIIcline" >><title>The Type II cline of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> through <m>z</m></title>
        <statement>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Given the three points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>Z</m> from the previous exercise, show again the point <m>O</m>, which is the center of the type I cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct segment <m>OZ</m>, and construct line <m>PQ</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the line perpendicular to segment <m>OZ</m> at the point <m>Z</m>. Call this line <m>m</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Determine the point <m>C</m> at which line <m>m</m> intersects line <m>PQ</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the circle centered at <m>C</m> through <m>Z</m>.  This is the type II cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Hide intermediate constructions, so that you just see on the canvas the three points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>Z</m>, the type I cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>, and the type II cline of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> through <m>Z</m>.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Two comments: First, the construction of the type II cline also assumes <m>Z</m> is not on the line through <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.  Second, <em>Geogebra</em> does not have a built-in tool for constructing type II clines, but we can create a custom tool that achieves this.  More on this below.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>     
    </worksheet>
    <p>
      Remark: The file you open in the next worksheet has this type II cline construction saved as a custom tool.  You can create your own custom tools in <em>Geogebra Classic</em> (but not other Geogebra Apps, as far as I know). A custom tool is super useful if you expect to repeat a particular construction often in a <em>Geogebra</em> project.  Very roughly to create a custom tool based on a construction you've done in <em>Geogebra Classic</em>, begin by selecting the <em>tools</em> option from the main drop-down menu, (the three bars icon in the upper right portion of the <em>Geogebra</em> window).
    </p>
<worksheet><title>Geogebra Worksheet 3: Constructing figures in <m>(\mathbb{D},{\cal H})</m></title>
        <p>
          Open the file <em>hyp_plane.ggb</em> which can be accessed here: <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/classic/yuxwfyp8">hyperbolic plane</url>.
        </p>
      <exercise><title>The hyperbolic line through <m>p</m> and <m>q</m></title>
        <statement>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Plot two points in <m>\mathbb{D}</m>, and label them <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.  Then use the <c>reflect about circle</c> tool to plot <m>P^\prime</m>, the point symmetric to <m>P</m> with respect to the unit circle.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the circle through <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>P^\prime</m>, call this circle <m>c</m>.  The hyperbolic line through <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is the portion of this circle inside <m>\mathbb{D}</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Plot the two ideal points of the hyperbolic line through <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, and label these points <m>U</m> and <m>V</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic line through <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, and then hide all intermediate constructions, so that we just see <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, the hyperbolic line through them, and the ideal points <m>U</m> and <m>V</m>.  Drag <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> around to make sure your construction works dynamically.           
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>The hyperbolic line connecting ideal points <m>u</m> and <m>v</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Plot two ideal points, <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>, and determine a way to construct the hyperbolic line joining them.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>The hyperbolic circle centered at <m>P</m> through <m>Q</m></title>
        <statement>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Given the two points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> in <m>\mathbb{D}</m>, show again <m>P^\prime</m>, the point symmetric to <m>P</m> with respect to the unit circle.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the type II cline of <m>P</m> and <m>P^\prime</m> that goes through <m>Q</m> by using the custom tool <c>typeIIcline</c> included in the file you opened (look for the wrench).  (See <xref ref="wk-typeIIcline" /> for this construction.)  
              This is the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>P</m> through <m>Q</m>.  You are welcome!
            </li>
            <li>
              Move <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> around to get a feel for how hyperbolic circles look in our disk model, and to make sure your construction works dynamically.
            </li>
            Position <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> to maximize the coolness quotient of your hyperbolic circle.
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>Construct the perpendicular bisector to segment <m>PQ</m></title>
      <statement>
        <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Use the <c>typeIIcline</c> tool to construct the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>P</m> through <m>Q</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>Q</m> through <m>P</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic line through the two points at which these circles intersect.  This line is the perpendicular bisector of segment <m>PQ</m>.  The construction is identical to the one used in Euclidean geometry.
            </li>
          </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise><title>There need not exist a hyperbolic circle through three points in <m>(\mathbb{D},{\cal H})</m></title>
    <statement>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          Hide all constructions execpt <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and the perpendicular bisector of <m>PQ</m>.  Then plot a new point, label it <m>T</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Construct perpendicular bisectors <m>PT</m> and <m>QT</m>, hiding all intermediate constructions afterwards, so we just see the three points and the three perpendicular bisectors.
        </li>
        <li>
          Find positions for <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>T</m> inside <m>\mathbb{D}</m> in which these three perpendicular bisectors do not intersect.
        </li>
        <li>
          For points in such positions, convince yourself that no hyperbolic circle will go through these three points.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>  
