<worksheet><title>Geogebra Worksheet 4: Measurement in <m>(\mathbb{D},{\cal H})</m></title>
        <p>
          Begin by opening the Geogebra file with the custom tools for constructions in the disk model <m>(\mathbb{D},{\cal H})</m>: <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/classic/bbuxpqrv">hyperbolic tools</url>.
        </p>
      <exercise><title>Quick calculations using custom tools</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Record your solutions to these quick calculations in the upper left portion of your canvas using the ABC text tool (grouped with the slider tool - two to the left of the custom tools), as will be demonstrated. </p>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic segment <m>AB</m> where <m>A = .2 + .3i</m> and <m>B = .4-.5i</m>, then determine <m>d_H(A,B)</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic triangle <m>\Delta ABC</m> where <m>A, B</m> are as above, and <m>C = -.3 + .3i</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              Determine the angle at each point in this triangle, and then compute the area of this triangle.  Be sure you convert your angles to radians before you use our triangle area formula.  Do this calculation in <em>Geogebra.</em>
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>D = -.5i</m> through <m>E = -.2-.5i</m>.  If <m>F</m> is any point on this circle, what is <m>d_H(D,F)</m>?
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>Once you have answered these questions and recorded them at left, you may hide the  constructions you made to solve them (or delete if your written answers do not depend on them). </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise><title>Angle of Parallelism</title>
      <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose Bormit is at point <m>Z</m> in the hyperbolic plane, and he sees a road up ahead, which is a hyperbolic line <m>l</m>.
      </p>    
        <ol label="a.">
          <li>
            Model this scenario.  That is, construct an arbitrary hyperbolic line <m>L</m> in the hyperbolic plane and plot a point <m>Z</m> not on <m>l</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Construct the hyperbolic line through <m>Z</m> that is orthogonal to <m>l</m>.  We don't have a tool that does this directly, but you can construct it by first reflecting <m>Z</m> across two well-chosen clines.  Let <m>W</m> be the point at which the two lines intersect.  
          </li>
          <li>
            The length of hyperbolic segment <m>ZW</m> represents the perpendicular distance of <m>Z</m> to <m>l</m> - it is the shortest distance Bormit can walk to reach the road.  Compute this distance, and call it <m>d</m>.  
          </li>
          <li>
            Suppose <m>U</m> is an ideal point of hyperbolic line <m>l</m>.  The angle <m>\alpha = \angle ZWU</m> is called the angle of parallelism of point <m>Z</m> to line <m>l</m>.  Determine the angle <m>\alpha</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            It turns out that in hyperbolic geometry, knowing <m>\alpha</m> fixes <m>d</m>.  That is, Bormit can determine his distance to line <m>L</m> by measuring the angle of parallelism.  In an input cell at left, enter <m>-ln(tan(\alpha/2))</m>, assuming your angle of parallelism has label <m>\alpha</m>.  Check that this value matches the hyperbolic distance from <m>Z</m> to <m>W</m>.  We can prove that in general, <me>\tan(\alpha/2)= e^{-d}</me> (we will do this later, not now).
          </li>
          <li>
            Download your workbook as a .ggb file entitled parallelism_yourname.ggb and add it to your homework folder.
          </li>
          </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise><title>Hyperbolic Right Triangles</title>
        <statement>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              Open a new copy of <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/classic/bbuxpqrv">hyperbolic tools</url>
            </li>
            <li>
              Construct a right triangle in the hyperbolic plane, avoiding the origin (use the custom tools!).  Build the triangle in such a way that it stays a right triangle if the points are moved around.
            </li>
            <li>
              Determine the lengths of the three sides of this triangle.  Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> denote the leg lengths, and <m>c</m> denote the hypotenuse length.
            </li>
            <li>
              Does <m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2</m>?  If not, which is bigger, <m>a^2 + b^2</m> or <m>c^2</m>? Is this always the case as the triangle moves around?
            </li>
            <li>
              One way to tackle the previous question would be to input <m>a^2 + b^2 - c^2</m> into a cell to see whether we get a positive, negative, or 0 value (and then move points around to see if this changes).  In a new input cell, type <m>\cosh(a)\cdot \cosh(b)-\cosh(c)</m>.  What value does this take as you move the triangle around?
            </li>
            <li>
              Yes, we can prove that in a hyperbolic right triangle with side lengths <m>a, b</m> and hypotenuse <m>c</m>, <m>\cosh(a)\cosh(b)=\cosh(c)</m>.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    <exercise><title>BONUS: Construct the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>p</m> with radius <m>r</m></title>
    <statement>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          Plot a point <m>p</m> in the hyperbolic plane, and set <m>r=4</m> in an input cell (which should create a slider for <m>r</m> - we can <m>0 \leq r \leq 5</m>, say.)
        </li>
        <li>
          Can you determine the value of the scalar <m>k</m> so that <m>d_H(kp,p)=r</m>?  Your answer should be of the formula for <m>k</m> that depends on <m>r</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          If you work that out algebraically, then one can compute <m>k</m> in Geogebra using your formula, then plot the scalar <m>kp</m>, and then plot the hyperbolic circle centered at <m>p</m> with radius <m>r</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>    
